          <para id="id2268242">The vectors <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">I</m:mi></m:math> and <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">J</m:mi></m:math> are not arbitrary. They are subject to the equation of continuity <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>∇</m:mi><m:mo>•</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="bold">A</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>. The effect of this condition is to make <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">I</m:mi></m:math> and <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">J</m:mi></m:math> behave like space and surface currents of something which is nowhere created or destroyed. In the electromagnetic field they usually represent currents of electricity. In hydrodynamic fields they represent vorticity. If <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">A</m:mi></m:math> is everywhere solenoidal, the following three equations must then be everywhere satisfied.</para>
          <equation id="id2268331">
